                <head>385. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On January 28, the House Committee on Government Operations released its First
                    Report on “United States Aid Operations in Iran.” The report was the work of the
                    Subcommittee on International Operations headed by Representative <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPJ1">Porter Hardy, Jr.</persName>, of Virginia. Department of
                    State and international Cooperation Administration officials had cooperated with
                    the <persName corresp="#p_HPJ1">Hardy</persName> Subcommittee investigation by
                    agreeing to provide background information and documentation, classified or
                    otherwise. (Memorandum from L.J. Saccio to <persName corresp="#p_HJB1"
                        >Hollister</persName> and memorandum for the files, both April 11, 1956;
                    Washington National Records Center, <gloss target="#t_ICA1">ICA</gloss>
                    Director’s Files: FRC 61 A 32, Box 309, Iran)</p>
                <p>The report was highly critical of the United States aid and technical assistance
                    program in Iran. (U.S. House of Representatives, 85th Congress, 1st Session,
                    House Report No. 10, “United States Aid Operations in Iran,” January 28, 1957,
                    pages 2–6)</p>
            </div>
